.\" wifi-tui.1 - manual page for wifi-tui
.\" Written in mdoc(7) format for FreeBSD.
.\"
.\" Render with:
.\"   man ./wifi-tui.1
.\"   mandoc -T utf8 wifi-tui.1 | less
.\"
.Dd April 30, 2026
.Dt WIFISCAN 1
.Os FreeBSD 14.4
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh NAME
.Nm wifi-tui
.Nd interactive ncurses TUI for IEEE 802.11 wireless network scanning
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl i Ar interface
.Op Fl r Ar seconds
.Op Fl s Ar column
.Ar interface
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a terminal-based wireless LAN scanner for
.Fx 14.4 .
It uses the
.Xr net80211 4
.Dv SIOCG80211
ioctl interface to trigger active scans and read cached scan results,
presenting them in a live-updating
.Xr ncurses 3
TUI.
.Pp
The display has two views:
.Bl -tag -width ".Em Detail pane"
.It Em List view
A scrollable table of all visible access points, updated automatically
every
.Ar seconds
seconds.
Columns show SSID, BSSID, channel, frequency, RSSI, security mode,
and beacon interval.
.It Em Detail pane
A full-screen information panel for the selected access point, opened by
pressing
.Sy Enter .
It shows identity, radio, 802.11 protocol, and security attributes,
a live RSSI bar, and an ASCII bar chart of historical signal strength.
.El
.Pp
.Nm
must be run as
.Sy root
or with sufficient privilege to perform
.Xr ioctl 2
calls on the 802.11 interface.
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh OPTIONS
.Bl -tag -width "-r seconds"
.It Fl i Ar interface
Wireless interface to scan
.Pq e.g. Ar wlan0 .
Equivalent to supplying
.Ar interface
as a bare positional argument.
.It Fl r Ar seconds
Auto-refresh interval in seconds.
The scan is re-triggered and the display updated this often.
Minimum value is 1.
Default is
.Sy 3 .
.It Fl s Ar column
Initial sort column index
.Pq Sy 0 No \(en Sy 6 .
See
.Sx SORT COLUMNS
below.
Default is
.Sy 4
.Pq RSSI, descending .
.It Fl h
Print a short usage summary and exit.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh SORT COLUMNS
.Bl -column "Index" "Header" "Description" -compact
.It Sy Index Ta Sy Header Ta Sy Description
.It 0 Ta SSID Ta Network name (lexicographic)
.It 1 Ta BSSID Ta Access point MAC address
.It 2 Ta CH Ta 802.11 channel number
.It 3 Ta FREQ Ta Channel frequency in MHz
.It 4 Ta RSSI Ta Received signal strength (default)
.It 5 Ta SEC Ta Security mode (Open < WPA < WPA2)
.It 6 Ta BCN Ta Beacon interval in TUs
.El
.Pp
The active sort column is indicated by a
.Sq v
.Pq descending
or
.Sq ^
.Pq ascending
suffix in the column header.
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh KEY BINDINGS
.Ss List View
.Bl -tag -width "PgUp / PgDn"
.It Sy Enter
Open the detail pane for the currently selected access point.
.It Sy q , Q , Esc
Quit
.Nm .
.It Sy r
Force an immediate rescan without waiting for the refresh timer.
.It Sy Up , Down
Move the selection one row up or down.
.It Sy PgUp , PgDn
Move the selection ten rows up or down.
.It Sy Home , End
Jump to the first or last access point in the list.
.It Sy 0 No \(en Sy 6
Sort by the corresponding column index immediately.
.It Sy s
Advance the sort column to the next column
.Pq wraps around .
.It Sy S
Retreat the sort column to the previous column
.Pq wraps around .
.It Sy R
Toggle between ascending and descending sort order.
.It Sy ?
Toggle the key-binding help bar at the bottom of the screen.
.El
.Ss Detail Pane
.Bl -tag -width "Esc / q / Enter"
.It Sy Esc , q , Q , Enter
Close the detail pane and return to the list view.
.It Sy r
Force an immediate rescan.
Useful to accumulate more samples in the signal history graph.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh DETAIL PANE
The detail pane is divided into four sections.
.Ss Identity
.Bl -tag -width "Extensions"
.It Sy SSID
Service Set Identifier.
Displays
.Em <hidden>
for networks that suppress SSID broadcast.
.It Sy BSSID
Basic Service Set Identifier; the MAC address of the access point radio.
.It Sy Band
Radio band:
.Em 2.4\ GHz ,
.Em 5\ GHz ,
or
.Em 6\ GHz (Wi-Fi\ 6E) .
.It Sy PHY Mode
Protocol generation detected from Information Elements:
.Em 802.11b/g ,
.Em 802.11a ,
.Em 802.11n\ (Wi-Fi\ 4) ,
.Em 802.11ac\ (Wi-Fi\ 5) ,
or
.Em 802.11ax\ (Wi-Fi\ 6/6E) .
.It Sy Channel
802.11 channel number derived from the reported frequency,
followed by the frequency in MHz.
.It Sy Extensions
PHY capabilities detected from beacon Information Elements:
.Em HT(n)
for 802.11n High-Throughput,
.Em VHT(ac)
for 802.11ac Very High-Throughput,
.Em HE(ax)
for 802.11ax High-Efficiency.
.El
.Ss Signal
.Bl -tag -width "Signal History"
.It Sy RSSI
Received Signal Strength Indicator in dBm, colour-coded:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
.Em Green :
.No >= \(mi60\ dBm
.Pq strong
.It
.Em Yellow :
\(mi61 to \(mi75\ dBm
.Pq fair
.It
.Em Red :
.No < \(mi75\ dBm
.Pq weak
.El
An inline ASCII bar
.Ql [ ###....... ]
visualises the value on a \(mi100 to \(mi30\ dBm scale.
.It Sy Noise Floor
Measured noise floor in dBm.
.It Sy SNR
Signal-to-Noise Ratio in dB
.Pq RSSI \(mi Noise floor .
Annotated as
.Em good
.Pq >= 25\ dB ,
.Em fair
.Pq >= 15\ dB ,
or
.Em poor
.Pq < 15\ dB .
.It Sy Signal History
A vertical bar chart of the last 64 RSSI samples, one sample per scan
cycle.
The Y-axis runs from \(mi100\ dBm
.Pq bottom
to \(mi30\ dBm
.Pq top .
Each bar is drawn with
.Sq |
characters and capped with
.Sq ^
at the peak.
Bars are colour-coded with the same green/yellow/red scale as RSSI.
Time increases left to right; the newest sample is always at the right
edge.
.El
.Ss 802.11
.Bl -tag -width "Beacon Interval"
.It Sy Beacon Interval
Interval between beacon frames in TUs
.Pq Time Units; 1\ TU\ =\ 1.024\ ms ,
followed by the approximate value in milliseconds.
.It Sy ERP Info
Value of the Extended Rate PHY information element
.Pq raw hex byte .
A non-zero value indicates that legacy
.Pq 802.11b
stations are present in the BSS.
.It Sy Capabilities
Raw capability information field in hex, followed by decoded flags:
.Em ESS
.Pq infrastructure mode ,
.Em IBSS
.Pq ad-hoc mode ,
.Em Privacy
.Pq encryption required ,
.Em ShortPreamble ,
.Em ShortSlot .
.It Sy Supported Rates
Basic rates are prefixed with
.Sq * .
Values are in Mbps.
Long rate lists are wrapped across multiple lines.
.El
.Ss Security
.Bl -tag -width "Short preamble"
.It Sy Mode
Highest security mode detected, in descending order of strength:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
.Em WPA2/RSN (802.11i)
\(em RSN Information Element found
.It
.Em WPA (TKIP)
\(em WPA vendor IE found
.It
.Em WEP (legacy)
\(em Privacy capability bit set but no WPA/RSN IE
.It
.Em Open (no encryption)
\(em no encryption indicators found
.El
Encrypted modes are displayed in green; open in red.
.It Sy WPA IE
Whether a WPA vendor-specific Information Element
.Pq OUI 00:50:F2, type 0x01
was found in the beacon.
.It Sy RSN IE
Whether an RSN
.Pq Robust Security Network
Information Element
.Pq element ID 48
was found in the beacon.
.It Sy Privacy bit
State of the Privacy flag in the Capability Information field.
.It Sy Short preamble
State of the Short Preamble capability flag.
.It Sy Short slot
State of the Short Slot Time capability flag.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh DISPLAY COLOURS
.Nm
uses terminal colours when the
.Ev TERM
environment variable indicates a colour-capable terminal.
.Bl -tag -width "Yellow"
.It Sy Green
Strong RSSI
.Pq >= \(mi60\ dBm ,
encrypted security modes, graph bars for strong signal.
.It Sy Yellow
Medium RSSI
.Pq \(mi61 to \(mi75\ dBm ,
countdown timer in the status bar.
.It Sy Red
Weak RSSI
.Pq < \(mi75\ dBm ,
open or unencrypted networks.
.It Sy Cyan
Column headers, box-drawing borders, field labels, status bar.
.It Sy Blue
Title bar, section header bars in the detail pane.
.It Sy White
Currently selected row, value fields in the detail pane.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh IMPLEMENTATION NOTES
.Ss FreeBSD 14.4 ioctl constraints
.Bl -bullet
.It
The
.Va i_len
field of
.Vt struct ieee80211req
is
.Vt int16_t
.Pq signed 16-bit .
The scan-result buffer is therefore capped at 32767 bytes
.Pq Dv INT16_MAX ,
which accommodates approximately 100 access points.
A buffer larger than this causes
.Va i_len
to wrap to a negative value, and the kernel returns
.Er EFAULT
.Pq \(dqBad address\(dq .
.It
Active scans must be triggered with
.Dv SIOCG80211
and
.Dv IEEE80211_IOC_SCAN_REQ .
Using
.Dv SIOCS80211
returns
.Er EINVAL
on FreeBSD 14.
.It
The struct fields
.Va isr_chan
and
.Va isr_beacon_int
do not exist in FreeBSD 14.
The channel number is derived from
.Va isr_freq
using:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
2.4\ GHz:
.Li (freq \- 2407) / 5
.It
5\ GHz:
.Li freq / 5 \- 1000
.It
6\ GHz:
.Li (freq \- 5950) / 5 + 1
.El
The beacon interval is read from
.Va isr_intval .
.It
Variable-length data
.Pq SSID, Mesh ID, Information Elements
begins at
.Va isr_ie_off
bytes from the start of
.Vt struct ieee80211req_scan_result ,
not at
.Fn sizeof "struct ieee80211req_scan_result" .
.El
.Ss Signal history
Each scan cycle appends one RSSI sample per visible AP into a ring
buffer of
.Dv WIFI_RSSI_HISTORY
.Pq 64
entries.
Older samples are overwritten once the buffer is full.
The graph in the detail pane displays the most recent
.Em min(sample_count, graph_width)
samples.
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width "TERM"
.It Ev TERM
Used by
.Xr ncurses 3
to determine colour and capability support.
A value such as
.Dq xterm-256color
or
.Dq screen-256color
is recommended for full colour rendering.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width "wifi-tui.c"
.It Pa wifi.h
Shared type definitions
.Pq Vt wifi_ap_t , Vt wifi_state_t ,
constants, and scan API declarations.
.It Pa wifi.c
.Xr net80211 4
ioctl implementation: socket creation, scan trigger, result fetch,
IE parsing
.Pq RSN, WPA, HT, VHT, HE .
.It Pa tui.h
TUI context structure
.Pq Vt tui_ctx_t ,
sort column constants, action enum, and public API declarations.
.It Pa tui.c
.Xr ncurses 3
rendering: list view, detail pane, inline RSSI bar, ASCII signal
history graph, keyboard input handling.
.It Pa wifi-tui.c
Entry point: argument parsing, event loop, SIGWINCH handling.
.It Pa Makefile
BSD
.Xr make 1
build file; uses
.Pa bsd.prog.mk
when available, with explicit fallback rules otherwise.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh EXAMPLES
Scan
.Em wlan0
with the default 3-second refresh interval:
.Pp
.Dl sudo wifi-tui wlan0
.Pp
Scan with a 10-second refresh, initial sort by channel:
.Pp
.Dl sudo wifi-tui -i wlan0 -r 10 -s 2
.Pp
Build from source and run:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
make
sudo ./wifi-tui wlan0
.Ed
.Pp
Install to
.Pa /usr/local/bin :
.Pp
.Dl sudo make install
.Pp
Install to a custom prefix:
.Pp
.Dl sudo make PREFIX=/opt install
.Pp
Verify the manpage renders correctly before installing:
.Pp
.Dl mandoc -T utf8 wifi-tui.1 | less
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh DIAGNOSTICS
.Bl -diag
.It "scan failed -- check interface/privileges"
The
.Dv SIOCG80211
ioctl returned an error.
Ensure the interface exists
.Pq Xr ifconfig 8 ,
is brought up with
.Ql ifconfig Ar interface up ,
and that
.Nm
is run as root.
.It "No scan results for <ifname>. Try: ifconfig <ifname> scan"
The kernel scan cache is empty.
Populate it with:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
ifconfig wlan0 up
ifconfig wlan0 scan
.Ed
.It "SIOCG80211 (scan results): Bad address"
The buffer length overflowed
.Vt int16_t .
Verify that
.Dv WIFI_MAX_IELEN
in
.Pa wifi.h
is no larger than 32767.
.It "SIOCG80211 (scan req): Invalid argument"
The scan-request struct flags or ioctl number are wrong.
Ensure the trigger uses
.Dv SIOCG80211
.Pq not Dv SIOCS80211
with
.Dv IEEE80211_IOC_SCAN_ACTIVE | IEEE80211_IOC_SCAN_ONCE | IEEE80211_IOC_SCAN_NOPICK
and
.Va sr_duration
set to
.Dv IEEE80211_IOC_SCAN_FOREVER .
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr ifconfig 8 ,
.Xr wpa_supplicant 8 ,
.Xr net80211 4 ,
.Xr ncurses 3 ,
.Xr ioctl 2 ,
.Xr make 1 ,
.Xr mandoc 1
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh STANDARDS
.Nm
decodes fields defined in:
.Bl -bullet -compact
.It
IEEE Std 802.11-2020
.Pq Information Elements, Capability Information, ERP, HT/VHT/HE Capabilities
.It
Wi-Fi Alliance WPA Information Element specification
.Pq OUI 00:50:F2, type 0x01
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh AUTHORS
.Nm
was written as a demonstration of direct
.Xr net80211 4
ioctl usage from FreeBSD 14.4 userland.
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh CAVEATS
.Bl -bullet
.It
The scan-result buffer is limited to 32767 bytes by the
.Vt int16_t
.Va i_len
field.
In very dense RF environments this may silently truncate the AP list.
.Nm
prints a warning to
.Em stderr
when the buffer fills completely.
.It
RSSI and noise values are reported in units of 0.5\ dBm by the
FreeBSD net80211 stack and are displayed as integer dBm values
.Pq floor of the true value .
.It
PHY mode detection
.Pq HT/VHT/HE
relies on Information Elements present in beacon frames.
Some access points omit optional IEs; the reported mode may therefore
be less specific than the actual hardware capability.
.It
.Nm
performs passive observation only.
It does not associate with, authenticate to, or transmit on any network.
.El
.\" -------------------------------------------------------------------------
.Sh BUGS
.Bl -bullet
.It
The 6\ GHz band
.Pq Wi-Fi\ 6E
channel calculation uses a simplified formula and may be incorrect
for all regulatory channel plans outside the standard 5.925\(en7.125\ GHz range.
.It
Hidden SSIDs are displayed as
.Em <hidden>
and cannot be resolved by
.Nm
without a directed active probe to the specific BSSID, which is not
currently implemented.
.It
The signal history graph requires a minimum terminal height of
approximately 30 rows to render all four detail-pane sections without
truncation.
On shorter terminals, sections near the bottom are silently omitted.
.El
